# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: contiki-os
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] His father was professor of mathematics Andrejs Dunkels.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] His mother was professor Kerstin Vännman.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] His work is mainly focused on computer networking technology and distributed communication, for small embedded systems and devices and wireless sensor networks on the Internet.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] He attended the Swedish Institute of Computer Science where he earned Bachelor of Science (B.S.), Master of Science (M.S.) in 2001, and a Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.) in 2007.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] Dunkels is best known to the embedded community as the author of the uIP (micro-IP) and lwIP TCP/IP Internet protocol suite (stacks).
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] He invented protothreads and the operating system Contiki.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] The *MIT Technology Review* placed him on the TR35 list of world's top 35 innovators under 35, in 2009.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] His book *Interconnecting Smart Objects with IP: the Next Internet*, co-authored with Jean-Philippe Vasseur, and with a foreword by Vint Cerf, was published in 2010.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] He is a founder of the Internet Protocol for Smart Objects Alliance (IPSO Alliance), which promotes IP networking for smart objects such as embedded systems and wireless sensors, and author of the alliance's white paper.
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] Dunkels received the 2008 Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGOPS EuroSys Roger Needham PhD award for his PhD thesis "Programming Memory-Constrained Networked Embedded Systems".
[src:contiki-os/adam-dunkels] Many of Dunkels's small implementations are used in commercial products from companies, including Asea Brown Boveri (ABB), Altera, BMW, Cisco Systems, Ericsson, GE, Hewlett-Packard (HP), Volvo Technology, and Xilinx.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki gained popularity because of its built-in TCP/IP stack and lightweight preemptive scheduling over event-driven kernel.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The name *Contiki* comes from Thor Heyerdahl's famous Kon-Tiki raft.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki provides multitasking and a built-in Internet Protocol Suite (TCP/IP stack); it needs about 10 kilobytes of random-access memory (RAM) and 30 kilobytes of read-only memory (ROM).
[src:contiki-os/contiki] A full system, including a graphical user interface, needs about 30 kilobytes of RAM.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] A new branch has recently been created, known as Contiki-NG: The OS for Next Generation IoT Devices.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki is designed to run on types of hardware devices that are severely constrained in memory, power, processing power, and communication bandwidth.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] A typical Contiki system has memory on the order of kilobytes, a power budget on the order of milliwatts, processing speed measured in megaHertz, and communication bandwidth on the order of hundreds of kilobits/second.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Such systems include many types of embedded systems, and old 8-bit computers.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki provides three network mechanisms: the uIP TCP/IP stack, which provides IPv4 networking, the uIPv6 stack, which provides IPv6 networking, and the Rime stack, which is a set of custom lightweight networking protocols designed for low-power wireless networks.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The IPv6 stack was contributed by Cisco and was, when released, the smallest IPv6 stack to receive the *IPv6 Ready* certification.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The IPv6 stack also contains the *Routing Protocol for Low power and Lossy Networks* (RPL) routing protocol for low-power lossy IPv6 networks and the 6LoWPAN header compression and adaptation layer for IEEE 802.15.4 links.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Rime is an alternative network stack, for use when the overhead of the IPv4 or IPv6 stacks is prohibitive.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The Rime stack provides a set of communication primitives for low-power wireless systems.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The default primitives are single-hop unicast, single-hop broadcast, multi-hop unicast, network flooding, and address-free data collection.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The primitives can be used on their own or combined to form more complex protocols and mechanisms.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Many Contiki systems are severely power-constrained.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Battery-operated wireless sensors may need to provide years of unattended operation and with little means to recharge or replace batteries.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki provides a set of mechanisms to reduce the power consumption of systems on which it runs.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The default mechanism for attaining low-power operation of the radio is called ContikiMAC.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] With ContikiMAC, nodes can be running in low-power mode and still be able to receive and relay radio messages.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The Contiki system includes a sensor simulator called Cooja, which simulates Contiki nodes.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The nodes belong to one of the three following classes: a) emulated Cooja nodes, b) Contiki code compiled and executed on the simulation host, or c) Java nodes, where the behavior of the node must be reimplemented as a Java class.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] One Cooja simulation may contain a mix of sensor nodes from any of the three classes.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Emulated nodes can also be used to include non-Contiki nodes in a simulated network.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] In Contiki 2.6, platforms with the TI MSP430 and Atmel AVR microcontrollers can be emulated.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] To run efficiently on small-memory systems, the Contiki programming model is based on protothreads.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] A protothread is a memory-efficient programming abstraction that shares features of both multithreading and event-driven programming to attain a low memory overhead of each protothread.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] The kernel invokes the protothread of a process in response to an internal or external event.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Examples of internal events are timers that fire or messages being posted from other processes.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Examples of external events are sensors that trigger or incoming packets from a radio neighbor.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Protothreads are cooperatively scheduled.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Thus, a Contiki process must always explicitly yield control back to the kernel at regular intervals.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki processes may use a special protothread construct to block waiting for events while yielding control to the kernel between each event invocation.
[src:contiki-os/contiki] Contiki is supported by popular SSL/TLS libraries such as wolfSSL, which includes a port in its 3.15.5 release.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] lwIP is used by many manufacturers of embedded systems, including Intel/Altera, Analog Devices, Xilinx, TI, ST and Freescale.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] The focus of the lwIP network stack implementation is to reduce resource usage while still having a full-scale TCP stack.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] This makes lwIP suitable for use in embedded systems with tens of kilobytes of free RAM and room for around 40 kilobytes of code ROM.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Aside from the TCP/IP stack, lwIP has several other important parts, such as a network interface, an operating system emulation layer, buffers and a memory management section.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] The operating system emulation layer and the network interface allow the network stack to be transplanted into an operating system, as it provides a common interface between lwIP code and the operating system kernel.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] The network stack of lwIP includes an IP (Internet Protocol) implementation at the Internet layer that can handle packet forwarding over multiple network interfaces.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Both IPv4 and IPv6 are supported dual stack since lwIP v2.0.0 .
[src:contiki-os/lwip] For network maintenance and debugging, lwIP implements ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol).
[src:contiki-os/lwip] IGMP (Internet Group Management Protocol) is supported for multicast traffic management.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] While ICMPv6 (including MLD) is implemented to support the use of IPv6.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] lwIP includes an implementation of IPv4 ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) and IPv6 Neighbor Discovery Protocol to support Ethernet at the data link layer. lwIP may also be operated on top of a PPP (Point-to-Point Protocol) implementation at the data link layer.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] At the transport layer lwIP implements TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) with congestion control, RTT estimation and fast recovery/fast retransmit.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is implemented with experimental UDP-Lite extensions.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] lwIP provides a specialized no-copy application programming interface (API) for enhanced network stack performance.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Raw sockets, or raw pcbs (protocol control blocks), are provided depending on the API used.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] At the application layer the lwIP network stack may be supported through the implementation of the following protocols.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] The DNS (Domain Name System), an SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol) agent, in v1, v2 or v3, with private MIB (management information base) support and MIB compiler.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Operating systems that implement the lwIP TCP/IP stack may provide a range of supporting clients and servers at the application layer.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Such as an IPv4 DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) client or IPv4 link-local addresses (AutoIP).
[src:contiki-os/lwip] Specialized raw API applications include: an HTTP server, a SNTP client, a SMTP client, a NetBIOS nameserver, a mDNS responder, a MQTT client and a TFTP server.
[src:contiki-os/lwip] lwIP is used as network stack in ReactOS and Genode and can be used in Minix and GNU Hurd to implement network servers.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] A **protothread** is a low-overhead mechanism for concurrent programming.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] Protothreads function as stackless, lightweight threads, or coroutines, providing a blocking context cheaply using minimal memory per protothread (on the order of single bytes).
[src:contiki-os/protothread] Protothreads are used to accomplish a non-preempted form of concurrency known as cooperative multitasking and, therefore, do not incur context switch when yielding to another thread.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] Within a protothread, yielding is accomplished by utilizing Duff's device within a thread's function and an external variable used in within the switch statement.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] This allows jumping (resuming) from a yield upon another function call.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] In order to block threads, these yields may be guarded by a conditional so that successive calls to the same function will yield unless the guard conditional is true.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] A feature of protothreads relative to other implementations of coroutines, or proper threads, is that they are stackless.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] A disadvantage is that local variables within the protothread cannot be trusted to have retained their values across a yield to another context.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] They must retain their state through the use of static or external, often global, variables.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] An advantage is that they are very lightweight and therefore useful on severely memory constrained systems like small microcontrollers where other solutions are impractical or less desirable.
[src:contiki-os/protothread] The protothread concept was developed by Adam Dunkels and Oliver Schmidt, based on prior work by Simon Tatham and Tom Duff.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] The **uIP** is an open-source implementation of the TCP/IP network protocol stack intended for use with tiny 8- and 16-bit microcontrollers.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It was initially developed by Adam Dunkels of the Networked Embedded Systems group at the Swedish Institute of Computer Science, licensed under a BSD style license, and further developed by a wide group of developers.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] uIP can be very useful in embedded systems because it requires very small amounts of code and RAM.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It has been ported to several platforms, including DSP platforms.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] In October 2008, Cisco, Atmel, and SICS announced a fully compliant IPv6 extension to uIP, called uIPv6.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] uIP makes many unusual design choices in order to reduce the resources it requires. uIP's native software interface is designed for small computer systems with no operating system.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It can be called in a timed loop, and the call manages all the retries and other network behavior.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] The hardware driver is called after uIP is called. uIP builds the packet, and then the driver sends it, and optionally receives a response.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It is normal for IP protocol stack software to keep many copies of different IP packets, for transmission, reception and to keep copies in case they need to be resent. uIP is economical in its use of memory because it uses only one packet buffer.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] First, it uses the packet buffer in a half-duplex way, using it in turn for transmission and reception.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Also, when uIP needs to retransmit a packet, it calls the application code in a way that requests for the previous data to be reproduced.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Another oddity is how uIP manages connections.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Most IP implementations have one task per connection, and the task communicates with a task in a distant computer on the other end of the connection.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] In uIP, no multitasking operating system is assumed.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] On each call, uIP tries to serve a connection, making a subroutine call to application code that responds to, or sends data.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] The size of the connection array is a number that can be adjusted when uIP is recompiled.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] uIP is fully compliant with the RFCs that define TCP, UDP and IP.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It also implements the mandatory maintenance protocol ICMP.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] uIP 0.9 is the version with the least dependence on operating systems, the smallest resource use, and the only version that presents a pure event loop API, but in its original form does not support IP version 6, only the older, more common IPv4.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It may be used in embedded systems with very small amounts of resources.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] It was delivered with a set of examples of higher-level protocols that also run on an event loop system, including HTTP (a simple web server), SMTP (simple mail transmission protocol), FTP (file transfer protocol), telnet (terminal emulation), and others.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Despite the examples and its small size, uIP 0.9 can be difficult to apply because it does not use any form of socket API.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] uIP is widely used code with well-known weaknesses.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] The design minimizes and separates 32-bit arithmetic so that it can be adjusted or optimized for 8 and 16-bit CPUs.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Also, 16-bit software timers (common on small microcontrollers) can overflow and cause defective operation.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] This can be fixed with a timer system that does not overflow (e.g. the timers count down or use modular arithmetic).
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Another issue is that its single packet buffer can have substantial throughput problems because a PC host usually delays the "ACK" packet, waiting for more packets.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] In slow, serial port implementations, the ack-throughput can be fixed by modifying uIP to send every packet as two half-packet fragments. uIP systems with fast ethernet or WiFi can modify the hardware driver to send every packet twice.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Some PCs do not correctly respond to a fast uIP system on a local Ethernet, because the uIP system can start a responding packet before the PC is ready to receive it.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] The solution is to call the uIP system less frequently in the main loop (Windows PCs are designed for a response time of about 1 millisecond).
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Typical implementations of uIP have a fixed IP address, which can make them impractical in real networks, although some have implemented DHCP.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Later versions of uIP, including the reference version of uIPv6, are integrated with Contiki, an operating system that uses coroutines for cooperative multitasking.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Contiki provides the multitasking needed by a simplified socket API, simplifying the use of uIP.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] These versions may be less popular than 0.9 however.
[src:contiki-os/uip-micro-ip] Many examples of embedded code do not use them.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:contiki-os/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
